column2: COVID-19 Vaccinations By Lower Tier Local Authority (LTLA) of Residence and Age Group
The number of people who have been vaccinated for COVID-19, split by LTLA of residence and age group, as reported to the date of publication.
National Immunisation Management Service (NIMS), NHS Foundry
The data in this release includes all vaccinations administered in England, even if individuals vaccinated do not have an NHS number or are no longer resident in the population.

column37: Cumulative Total Doses (1st and 2nd doses) to Date

column1: 1. Data was extracted from the National Immunisation Management Service via NHS Foundry on 9th July 2021.

2. These are provisional data providing timely daily updates of vaccinations reported by midnight of 8th July 2021. Not all vaccinations administered up to this date will be included in these figures. At 1st July 2021, 90.3% of vaccinations recorded in the NIMS database were reported within 1 day of being administered and 97.3% of vaccinations were reported within 7 days.

3. The statistics published weekly will differ from those presented here as the weekly figures only cover individuals who have an NHS number and are currently alive in the resident population. The weekly figures also capture more events due to be being extracted at a later point. Data on residence and age in this release is taken from the NHS Master Patient Index, whereas they are taken from the National Immunisation Management Service in the weekly publications.
4. Lower Tier Local Authority (LTLA) is as defined at April 2021. An individual's LTLA of residence is taken from the NHS Master Patient Index.
5. The sum of LTLAs will not equal the England total. This is due to a number of individuals vaccinated in England with a registered address in Scotland or Wales or where their address is unknown.
6. Age is as at 31st March 2021 and is taken from the NHS Master Patient Index.

7. These figures include all individuals identified in the relevant age bands. For example 80+ includes all people who have been vaccinated who are aged 80+ and does not exclude those who are in a higher priortiy group for vaccination as set out by the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (i.e. care home residents). The under 25 age group includes individuals aged under 18 who will have been vaccinated either because they fall into one of the JCVI priority cohorts (i.e. they are 16+ and have either been identified as at risk or a carer, are clinically extremely vulnerable, or are a health or social care worker), or based on JCVI advice that children under 16 at very high risk of exposure and serious outcomes, such as those with severe neuro-disabilities that require residential care, should be offered vaccination.
8. The sum of the age groups across doses will not equal the cumulative total. This is due to a number of individuals with an unknown age.
